---
// src/pages/index.astro
import CONFIG from '../config/conf'
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro'
---

<BaseLayout
    headTitle="YINI: Clean, human-friendly configuration format"
    headDescription="INI-inspired config with cleaner structure, richer syntax, simple rules."
>
    <section class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-4 py-2 text-center">
        <h1 class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight md:text-5xl">
            {CONFIG.text.headline}
        </h1>
        <p class="mt-3 text-base text-gray-600 md:text-lg">
            {CONFIG.text.elevatorPitch}
        </p>

        <div class="mt-6 flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-3">
            <a href="/get-started" class="btn btn-primary"> Get Started </a>

            <!-- !!Temp disabled
            <a href="/playground" class="btn btn-outline"> Open Playground </a>
            -->

            <a href="/yini-tutorial" class="inline-block underline">
                Quick tutorial
            </a>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>TL;DR — Try YINI in three quick steps</h2>
        <h3>1. Create a text file and save it</h3>
        Save below two rows in a file as <code>config.yini</code>:<br />
        <section class="code">
            <pre><code class="language-yini">{`^ App
name = 'Hello'`}</code></pre>
        </section>
        ⚠️ Make sure, you saved the file with the extension <code>.yini</code
        >and not with <code>.txt</code>.

        <h3>2. Run this line in terminal</h3>
        Open a terminal (like bash or CMD) at the same place where you saved the
        above file.<br />
        Then run this line: <code>npx yini-cli parse config.yini</code><br />

        <h3>3. The result</h3>
        This will ouput the following result as JavaScript (JS):
        <section class="code">
            <pre><code class="language-yini">{`{ App: { name: 'Hello' } }`}</code></pre>
        </section>

        <h3>BONUS. If you want the result a bit prettier</h3>
        Then run this line instead: <code
            >npx yini-cli parse config.yini --pretty</code
        >,
    </section> which gives the restult:
    <section class="code">
        <pre><code class="language-yini">{`{
    "App": {
        "name": "Hello"
    }
}
`}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Example</h2>
        <h3>YINI code:</h3>
        <section class="code">
            <pre><code class="language-yini">{`^ App
  name = "My App"
  version = "1.2.3"
  pageSize = 25
  darkTheme = off
`}</code></pre>
        </section>

        <h3>Parsed output (JS):</h3>
        <section class="code">
            <pre><code class="language-yini">{`{
    "App": {
        "name": "My App",
        "version": "1.2.3",
        "pageSize": 25,
        "darkTheme": false
    }
}`}</code></pre>
        </section>
    </section>

    <section class="why-yini">
        <h2>Why YINI?</h2>
        INI is simple but unstructured. YAML is powerful but can be hard to read
        and lint. JSON is precise but verbose for humans. YINI blends the best parts:
        readable keys, clean nesting, and a versioned specification — so it behaves
        the same everywhere.
        <ul>
            <li>
                <strong>Readable & Familiar</strong> — learn it in minutes if you
                know INI
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Structured</strong> — sections, arrays, objects, clear nesting
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Predictable</strong> — fewer gotchas; strict/lenient modes
                available
            </li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <h2>A Bigger Example</h2>
    <section class="code">
        <pre><code class="language-yini">{`^ App
name = "Demo"
version = "1.0.0"
features = [ "search", "dark-mode" ]  # comments allowed

^ Database
host = "localhost"
port = 5432
auth = { user: "admin", pass: "secret" }`}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section class="benefits">
        <ul>
            <li>
                <strong>Familiar</strong> — learn it in minutes if you know INI
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Structured</strong> — sections, arrays, objects, clear nesting
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Predictable</strong> — fewer gotchas; strict/lenient modes
                available
            </li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="try">
        <h2>Try it</h2>
        <p>In your terminal (CMD or bash), write the following:</p>
        <pre><code>npm i -D yini-cli
yini validate ./config.yini</code></pre>
        <!-- 
        !!Temp disabled
        <p><a href="/playground" class="btn">Open Playground</a></p>
         -->
    </section>

    <p class="mt-3 text-base text-gray-600 md:text-base">
        <h2>About</h2>
        <p>
            YINI is a new configuration format, <strong
                >formalized in 2025</strong
            >. It's a structured configuration format designed for clarity, easy
            nesting, and strict validation.
        </p>
        <p>
            The format's syntax and behavior are defined in the
            <strong>YINI Specification</strong>, currently at
            <strong>Version 1.0 — Candidate Release</strong>.
        </p>
        <p>
            YINI was created and is maintained by Marko K. Seppänen as an
            open-source project under the <a
                href="https://github.com/YINI-lang"
                target="_blank"
                rel="noopener noreferrer"
                class="text-slate-400 no-underline hover:text-sky-300 hover:underline"
                >YINI-lang organization</a
            >.
            <p>
                The specification, tooling, and ecosystem are actively evolving
                toward the first stable release.
            </p>
        </p>

        <section>
            <h2>Next steps</h2>
            <li>
                ➡️ <a href="/get-started">Get Started</a><br />
                <em>Learn how to install and use YINI.</em>
            </li>
            <li>
                ➡️ <a href="/yini-tutorial">Quick Tutorial</a><br />
                <em>5 minute guided walkthrough of YINI.</em>
            </li>
        </section>
    </p>
</BaseLayout>
